(1247, 'AMIA Form 7', 'In the movie and media studies it has always been a desire to annotate and analyze movies as easy as images. But the properties of the movie are so different from the static image. The motion picture has a continuous linearity and makes only sense in a dynamic state. Thus, this medium is difficult to grab and the researcher isn&#039;t able to write notes and commentaries directly to it. In addition these dynamic media need always a technical device to watch or hear them. In today&#039;s digital world it`s easier to do research in movies, because we can work with only one technical device -- the computer.\r\n\r\nFor movie research several video transcription tools exist. But for qualitative data analysis, none of them is able to do annotations in a column-based way. And that would be important to create a protocol of a sequence with different aspects (camera, persons, locations or other comments). At the moment we have to use different software-solutions like a movie player and a text editor. This solution is awkward and at the end we&#039;ve got a sequence protocol, that is not directly connected with the movie(-sequence).\r\n\r\nTo obviate such obstacles, we are developing a virtual research platform called SALSAH (System for Annotation and Linkage of Sources in Arts and Humanities), which is purely web based. On this tool it is possible to connect with different project partners and their collections of sources. SALSAH working for that with a RDF-database. At the moment we are able to work (to mark, to annotate, to link) with images or books. And now we are going to add a new module for dynamic sources like sound or motion picture. The goal is, to transliterate movies on a easy way and to link marked sequences with other media types.', 11, 36, '', 0, 0, 0, '', 0, '2013-05-07 13:22:34', NULL),
(1248, 'AMIA Form 2', 'SALSAH Movie Player: Annotation and Linkage in a multimedia environment', 0, 0, 'http://www.surveymonkey.com/s/A2013', 0, 0, 0, '', 0, '2013-05-07 11:46:56', NULL),
(1249, 'AMIA Form 9', 'We are presenting a tool for annotations and linking of movie sources on a web based platform. Thus the audience needs a knowledge in web-technology (php, javascript), in database-management (RDF) and in video-annotation. ', 0, 0, '', 0, 0, 0, '', 0, '2013-05-07 11:36:35', NULL),
(1250, 'AMIA Form 10', 'The tool is a open-source-software solution, that everyone can use, when he wants to work with SALSAH.  Video-Annotation is not only interesting for movie-researcher, but also for conservators, to mark sequences and comment them with editing-informations.', 0, 0, '', 0, 0, 0, '', 0, '2013-05-07 11:41:34', NULL),
(1251, 'AMIA Form 8', 'In the movie and media studies it has always been a desire to annotate and analyze movies as easy as images. But the properties of the movie are so different from the static image. Several video transcription tools exist, but none of them is able to do annotations in a column-based way. That would be important to create a protocol of a sequence with different aspects (camera, persons, locations or other comments).\r\nOn a existing virtual research environment called SALSAH (System for Annotation and Linkage of Sources in Arts and Humanities) we are developing a new module for dynamic media like motion picture or sound. The goal is, to transliterate movies on a easy way and to link marked sequences with other media types. The great advantage of this tool is, that it is purely web based and can connect with different institutions and their collections of sources.', 0, 0, '', 0, 0, 0, '', 0, '2013-05-07 12:46:39', NULL),
